Problem 6: ID vs Class

âœ… Your Answer: green
âœ” Correct â†’ ID (#para) has higher specificity (100) than class (.text, 10).
Final = green.

Problem 7: Inline Style vs CSS

âœ… Your Answer: purple
âœ” Correct â†’ Inline styles have the highest specificity (1000) compared to external/embedded CSS.
Final = purple.

Problem 8: !important vs Inline

âœ… Your Answer: orange
âœ” Correct â†’ Even though inline style is very strong, !important beats inline styles (unless inline also has !important).
Final = orange.

Problem 9: Multiple Classes

âœ… Your Answer: blue
âœ” Correct â†’ All three classes apply, but since they have the same specificity, the last one written in CSS wins.
Final = blue.

Problem 10: Inheritance + Override

âœ… Your Answer: pink
âœ” Correct â†’

body { color: brown; } â†’ would normally pass brown down.

div { color: inherit; } â†’ inherits brown from body.

But p { color: pink; } â†’ direct rule overrides inherited color.
Final = pink.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
  body {
    color: red;
    opacity: 0.5;
  }
  p {
    opacity: inherit;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>
  <p>Hello Opacity</p>
</body>
</html>


color: red; on body â†’ color is inherited by default, so <p> also gets red.

opacity: 0.5; on body â†’ opacity is NOT inherited by default.

But you wrote opacity: inherit; on <p> â†’ this forces it to take the parentâ€™s opacity.

So <p> has red color and opacity 0.5.

âš¡ Result:
ğŸ‘‰ Text "Hello Opacity" will appear red but slightly transparent (50%).





