âœ… 1. Inheritance

Some CSS properties are inherited by default (mainly text-related).

Others are NOT inherited by default (mainly box model & layout).

Inherited by default

color

font properties (font-family, font-size, etc.)

line-height

visibility

Not inherited by default

background

margin, padding

border

width, height

opacity

ğŸ‘‰ You can force inheritance:

p { background-color: inherit; }

âœ… 2. Cascading (Conflict Resolution Rules)

When multiple rules apply to the same element, CSS decides the winner in this order:

Importance

!important > everything else

Specificity

Inline styles â†’ 1000

ID selector â†’ 100

Class / attribute / pseudo-class â†’ 10

Element / pseudo-element â†’ 1

Source Order

If same specificity, the last declared rule wins.

âœ… 3. Specificity Examples
Selector	Specificity Score
p	1
.class	10
#id	100
p.class	11
div p	2
style="..."	1000
p { color:red !important; }	âˆ (beats all)
âœ… 4. Inheritance + Cascade Together

Example:

body { color: blue; }      /* inherited by children */
p { color: green; }        /* overrides inheritance */
#special { color: red; }   /* higher specificity */
p { color: purple !important; } /* final winner */


Final color for <p id="special">: purple âœ…

âœ… 5. Quick Analogy

Inheritance = traits passed from parents to children (like eye color).

Cascading = rules to solve conflicts when multiple styles apply (like deciding whose opinion wins).

Specificity = priority levels in those rules.

âš¡ Golden Rule:
ğŸ‘‰ !important > Inline > ID > Class > Element > Inherited




<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Georgia, serif;
      color: purple;
    }
    p {
      color: blue;
      font-size: 18px;
    }
    .special {
      color: green;
      font-family: "Courier New", monospace;
    }
    #unique {
      color: red;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <p>This is normal paragraph</p>
  <p class="special">This is special paragraph</p>
  <p id="unique" class="special">This is unique paragraph</p>
  <p style="color: orange;">This is inline styled paragraph</p>
</body>
</html>
Rule Analysis:
Body â†’ gives font = Georgia, color = purple

(inherited unless overridden)

p â†’ overrides:

color = blue

font-size = 18px

.special â†’ overrides for that class:

color = green

font-family = Courier New

#unique â†’ overrides:

color = red (ID beats class)

Inline style â†’ strongest (overrides everything with same property).

Final Output:
First <p> â†’ blue text, Georgia font, 18px

Second <p class="special"> â†’ green text, Courier New font, 18px

Third <p id="unique" class="special"> â†’ red text, Courier New font, 18px

Fourth <p style="color: orange;"> â†’ orange text, Georgia font, 18px

âœ… Answer Summary:

Normal â†’ Blue + Georgia

Special â†’ Green + Courier New

Unique â†’ Red + Courier New

Inline â†’ Orange + Georgia
